##### Alie Fink, Vincenzo Malo 

### Introduction
Brain lesions are defined as anatomical abnormalities in the brain. Lesions can result from a myriad of causes: stroke, fluid built-up, tumors, microbleeds, small vessel, disease, or hemorrhages (Wardlaw 2015). Lesions can result in cognitive impairment, problems in gait, dementia, depression, and in extreme cases, death (Merino 2019). 

Lesions are detectable on brain scans like computerized tomographies (CT) and magnetic resonance assays (MRI). Lesions are generally referred to as white matter hyperintensities (WMH), named from their characteristic white appearance on brain scans. Visualizing WMHs is essential to diagnosing and monitoring neurological diseases (Wardlaw, Merino). Lesion identification is done by individual physicians, which is time-consuming, costly, and can lead to many inaccuracies (Liew). Physicians must dedicate time out of their already overpacked schedules to identify and diagnose lesions. Additionally, one study rated the accuracy of physician raters for lesion diagnoses and found the average human performance for classifying scans as containing a lesion or not is 76% accurate +/- 0.14 (Liew). 

There is a need for high-throughput brain lesion diagnoses. To our knowledge, machine learning algorithms have not been widely implemented to solve this problem. Machine learning provides a unique solution to this problem. With a well-trained and validated algorithm, physicians could decrease the time spent analyzing brain scans, increase diagnostic accuracy, and standardize diagnosis across physicians. 

The present study aims to set up lesion diagnosis as a binary classification problem. Our central goal was to train a simple model using previously developed convolutional neural network (CNN) to diagnose lesions. We hypothesized that we could train a simple model to classify images as containing a lesion or not. Our hope was to achieve accuracy levels higher than 90% with a simple model to validate the ease of implementing automated diagnostic techniques to aid physicians. 

### Methods

##### Data: 

We started using a dataset titled Brain MRI Images for Brain Tumor Detection posted to Kaggle by Navoneel Chakrabarty. This data set contains MRI scans of participants with and without brain tumors. However, we shifted to optimizing our model for a different dataset titled Brain Tumor Images Dataset posted by Adedoyin Simeon because of a larger amount of better images. As such, the present study used an open-source data set of 200 computerized tomography (CT) scans. Half of the images contained brain hemorrhagic tumors. Our model seeks to classify these images (Figure 1) as non-tumor or tumor containing. Images came divided into folders for training (140 images), testing (20 images), and validation (40 images). All folders had equally represented tumor and non-tumor containing images.

##### Preprocessing
Images come divided into testing, training, and validation folders. Each folder then was divided into a Yes or No subfolder. Yes indicated images with lesions and no indicated images without. We first ran two models with the data and after getting results of around 80% accuracy, decided to revisit the data to see if there were problems with the data that may be tampering with accuracy. Next, using our domain knowledge, we omitted images from the training set that might alter preliminary results. Some images were scans of brain slices closer to the top of the skull. These images contain a higher amount of white area from the skull and might alter diagnostic outcome (Figure 2). Low resolution, blurry images were also omitted. However, since most images are taken at the same level, normalization is mostly already accounted for. In total 9 training images were removed from the training set and 9 test images were taken to replace them.
In our final model, we combined images from two data sets to increase the amount of available data. The training data set had 120 images with tumors and 118 images without tumors. The validation data had 20 images with tumors and 26 images without tumors. Future algorithms would need to account for these images.

##### Algorithm:

We chose to employ a convolutional neural network (CNN) for our model. CNNs allow for image characterization by identifying aspects of images. CNNs are algorithms characterized by convolutional layers. A convolutional layer takes a predetermined kernel and slides it over the pixels of an input image. A feature map is generated from the convolution of areas where the input image content matches that of the kernel. This process is repeated again on the feature map output with another kernel and the results are pooled together (Figure 3). CNNs allow for transfer learning, or the ability to apply the basic kernel layers to a variety of image classification problems without defining new kernels (Saha). The culmination of this analysis is a highly accurate classification of image content.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

###### Figure 3: Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) schematic (Saha).

FastAi is a pytorch library that has simple, widely accessible deep learning algorithms for public use. One such algorithm is the Fastai Vision library that provides simple functions for training CNNs (Tanner). The FastAi vision library CNN was trained on ImageNet datasets. ImageNet is an image database that contains hundreds of thousands of various images for research use (ImageNet). 

##### Specific model parameters:

The preliminary models made use of resnet18 with an image size of 250, which yielded poor accuracy and results. This led us to choose a larger image size of 525 for our next two models, which utilized resnet34 and resnet50 respectively. The first three models were trained on accuracy and the final on recall. The final model required a decreased image size in order to accommodate the larger data set due to problems with memory capacity. The image size was decreased to 300 and resnet50 was used. After checking the optimal training time and adjusting for it (5e-6 to 1e-5), there were no significant differences in model results, so the model was allowed to use defaults.
We chose to prioritize minimizing false negatives with our model. In our study, false negatives occur when our algorithm labels brain images with a tumor as healthy non-tumor brains. This is a significant danger for patients with tumors that are diagnosed as healthy, because it could result in death if the tumor is misdiagnosed. The danger of a false negative outweighs the danger of a false positive (a healthy brain diagnosed as having a tumor). We therefore chose our evaluation metric to be recall, because recall accounts for the higher cost associated with false negatives (Shung).

##### Epochs:

An epoch represents the number of times a data set is fed through a CNN (Sharma). This updates the model with each epoch to improve the result (Figure 3). Too many epochs and the model will memorize the given data. Too little epochs and the model will not be specific enough to accurately answer your question. We determined our number of epochs by evaluating the valid loss and the training loss. When the valid loss started to increase and exceed our training loss at an epoch, we decided to take the previous epoch as the number used in our model. Loss is the metric that evaluates how far the given data is from the predictive output of the model (Sharma).

### Results

The first three models we ran were trained on accuracy. By the end of the third model we had reached an accuracy of 82.5% - 85%, depending on where one decides to choose the final epoch. These models were not optimized for recall though so we switched to recall in our last model.

In this last model, we exceeded 90% recall. Our model could reliably predict whether an input image contained a lesion or tumor with 95% recall after 14 out of the 25 epochs. At the 15th epoch, the valid loss started increasing, suggesting that our model might be starting to overfit out data. After 25 epochs the recall ended at 90%, but our valid loss has exceeded our training loss, suggesting overfitting at the end. Additionally retraining the model seemed to overfit the data, so it would be best to stick with the former model in this case around 15 epochs

As we can see, the model fits the data well, having around 90-95% recall. The confusion matrix shows the optimized reduction of false negatives. Additionally the model rerun, shows only 1 false negative instead of 2. The most commonly reported errors show that the model is incapable of recognizing slight differences in intensity that may be due to other random error from the imaging or white matter tracts that may emerge in certain areas depending on how the image was adjusted.

### Conclusion

Our preliminary model performed well in diagnosing images with brain tumors from those that did not. We employed a simple machine learning strategy to solve a binary classification problem in neurology. These data provide convincing evidence for the utility of employing basic CNN models to aid physicians in diagnosing brain lesions. There are many future directions of our project:

First, though our model is over 90% accurate, no model will be 100% accurate. There will inevitably be a misdiagnosis from a computerized diagnostic software. When this occurs, if there is a significant dangerous outcome for a patient, who is culpable? This problem is rampant in applications of machine learning technology from medicine to self-driving cars and should be addressed before these algorithms are implemented.

Second, our model is only trained to diagnose large hemorrhagic brain tumors. Currently, our model is not trained to detect smaller, less pronounced brain lesions. White matter hyperintensities (WMH) can be quite small. Future directions of this project should be generalized to broader types of brain lesions.

Third, the location of a WMH is important for diagnostic and treatment purposes. The CNN approach can be expanded beyond a simple binary classification problem to characterize types of lesions by size, location, and shape. Doing so would provide immense utility for physicians to standardize and expedite diagnoses. Physicians could load images immediately into a diagnostic algorithm for results within seconds. Patients suffering from stroke, cancer, or multiple sclerosis could have fast, accurate diagnoses within minutes of finishing a CT or MRI.

In summary, our hypothesis of using fastai for tumor classification is supported. This project provides hope and support for incorporating relatively simple models into brain imaging technology to improve clinical outcomes. Future research should look into applying similar models in clinical settings.
